00:24:59,964 --> 00:25:03,064
Leave him, let's get out of here.

246
00:25:14,886 --> 00:25:17,286
So you're a cop killer now, Joseph?

247
00:25:17,426 --> 00:25:18,993
I didn't kill anybody.

248
00:25:20,460 --> 00:25:23,793
Looks like your friends were about to
take you on the dead man's drive.

249
00:25:24,295 --> 00:25:25,895
Dad, they're going to kill her.

250
00:25:27,447 --> 00:25:29,714
Well, we won't kill you, Joseph...

251
00:25:30,410 --> 00:25:33,210
...but some of my coworkers
would like a word.

252
00:25:33,410 --> 00:25:36,582
Please, Dad! Oh, I'm going to kill him!

253
00:25:38,522 --> 00:25:41,022
She's in the car with Donnie Gishler!

254
00:25:56,859 --> 00:25:59,459
I don't know what his skull's
made of but it isn't bone.

255
00:25:59,529 --> 00:26:01,962
In a coma two weeks.
No cranial bleeding.

256
00:26:02,014 --> 00:26:06,681
No loss of memory or speech disabilty.
His nose and half his ribs are broken.

257
00:26:07,284 --> 00:26:10,150
It'll be a long time before he doesn't
see any blood in the bowl. Go on in.

258
00:26:14,614 --> 00:26:17,014
Dad, where is she?

259
00:26:18,177 --> 00:26:19,310
Did they find her?

260
00:26:19,384 --> 00:26:21,610
We followed her and Donnie Gishler.

261
00:26:21,810 --> 00:26:24,710
His car went off the road
and into the ocean at 9:20.

262
00:26:26,685 --> 00:26:28,885
An officer from Beverly dove in lookin'
for them.

263
00:26:30,900 --> 00:26:33,200
Ended up in the hospital
for a week with hypothermia.

264
00:26:34,905 --> 00:26:39,505
She was Albert White's girl.
She betrayed you.

265
00:26:40,716 --> 00:26:42,649
She did...

266
00:26:42,977 --> 00:26:44,516
And?

267
00:26:44,805 --> 00:26:48,480
I'm crazy about her. Crazy isn't love.

268
00:26:49,533 --> 00:26:51,599
I saw your marriage for 18 years.
It wasn't love.

269
00:26:54,293 --> 00:26:56,793
No, no it wasn't.

270
00:26:59,029 --> 00:27:03,029
Anyway, she's gone. She's as
dead as your mother, God rest her..

271
00:27:07,809 --> 00:27:11,143
They caught up with Paolo in St. Albans,
about 10 miles from the border.

272
00:27:11,460 --> 00:27:13,694
A number of officers gave chase.

273
00:27:13,764 --> 00:27:17,094
He was struck by at least 14 rounds...

274
00:27:17,335 --> 00:27:18,699
...low for a cop killer.

275
00:27:20,923 --> 00:27:25,056
What about Dion?
It's possible he made the border.

276
00:27:42,848 --> 00:27:46,182
You were the child that was supposed to fix
the distance between me and your mother.

277
00:27:46,613 --> 00:27:48,113
were you aware of that?

278
00:27:50,694 --> 00:27:53,161
I was aware of the distance.

279
00:27:54,486 --> 00:27:56,953
People don't fix each other.

280
00:27:58,824 --> 00:28:02,324
They never become anything
but what they've always been.

281
00:28:02,649 --> 00:28:06,249
All we get sometimes is a little luck.

282
00:28:09,227 --> 00:28:12,593
Do not waste your's
pining for a dead girl.

283
00:28:12,909 --> 00:28:14,467
You make your own luck.

284
00:28:14,667 --> 00:28:17,734
Sometimes, sometimes it makes you.

285
00:28:26,814 --> 00:28:30,747
If he pleads guilty, I can take
the death penalty off the table.

286
00:28:37,585 --> 00:28:40,918
3 years out, 20 probation.

287
00:28:41,313 --> 00:28:44,580
Three years?
There are 3 dead police officers.

288
00:28:44,957 --> 00:28:46,457
And he didn't kill them.

289
00:28:50,643 --> 00:28:52,753
He may be the son
of the Deputy Superintendent...

290
00:28:52,953 --> 00:28:56,209
...but he will long know the
inside of the Charlestown Prison.

291
00:28:56,295 --> 00:29:00,024
I promise you. Chief Inspector,
I was demoted yesterday.

292
00:29:00,594 --> 00:29:04,061
Then we can leave unsaid the notion
I was going to dispell for you.

293
00:29:05,465 --> 00:29:08,465
I have no illusions.
I'm a practical man.

294
00:29:12,496 --> 00:29:15,363
The photograph is of a door
to a rowhouse in Back Bay...

295
00:29:15,375 --> 00:29:18,363
...where you have been keeping time
with a young man of Mexican descent.

296
00:29:19,112 --> 00:29:23,979
If you move the location of your
liasons, I will know within the hour.

297
00:29:32,066 --> 00:29:33,933
Let me see what I can do.

298
00:29:34,521 --> 00:29:37,221
Seeing what you can do
is of little interest to me.

299
00:29:38,274 --> 00:29:39,940
<i>Federal Prison Of Charleston</i>

300
00:29:51,292 --> 00:29:53,826
I pled guilty to
abetting armed robbery...

301
00:29:54,183 --> 00:29:58,183
...and was given 3 years and 4 months
in the Charlestown prison.

302
00:30:30,060 --> 00:30:32,794
If my father had lived 2 more weeks...

303
00:30:33,280 --> 00:30:35,413
I could have said goodbye.

304
00:31:24,349 --> 00:31:26,415
I got one guaranteed life...

305
00:31:28,001 --> 00:31:30,235
...and I was going to live it.

306
00:31:33,085 --> 00:31:37,285
I would use Maso and his
hatred for Albert to get me started.

307
00:31:37,414 --> 00:31:38,914
Funny, how things change.

308
00:31:39,768 --> 00:31:43,135
What happened to all the talk
about not being a gangster?

309
00:31:43,661 --> 00:31:46,461
Now you come to me looking for a job.

310
00:31:46,561 --> 00:31:48,061
I got nothin' left.

311
00:31:49,048 --> 00:31:50,781
I don'tt want to be a gangster.

312
00:31:51,670 --> 00:31:54,370
But I'll work for one if I
can get to Albert White.

313
00:31:54,719 --> 00:31:58,686
From what I heard in prison,
you're still the man to see about that.

314
00:31:58,831 --> 00:32:02,231
We ran Albert White
out of Boston like you heard.

315
00:32:02,366 --> 00:32:06,799
Now he's making a run to our
rum operation in central Florida.

316
00:32:06,923 --> 00:32:08,254
He won't stand by.

317
00:32:08,419 --> 00:32:11,986
It's true,
I could use someone who is committed...

318
00:32:12,086 --> 00:32:14,286
...to putting an end to Mr. White.

319
00:32:14,367 --> 00:32:15,667
You found your man right here.

320
00:32:15,925 --> 00:32:18,191
Your duty would always have to be...

321
00:32:18,195 --> 00:32:20,591
...to the Pescatore Family first,
then yourself second.

322
00:32:20,647 --> 00:32:23,247
Can you live with that? It sounds fair.

323
00:32:24,070 --> 00:32:26,503
I just need one guy,
Dion Bartolo from my old crew...

324
00:32:26,582 --> 00:32:27,703
...to help me go down there and set up.

325
00:32:27,978 --> 00:32:30,811
It's good to have someone you can trust.

326
00:32:34,598 --> 00:32:36,998
It's hot down there. I don't mind hot.

327
00:32:38,056 --> 00:32:40,156
You ain't never felt hot like this one.

328
00:32:40,206 --> 00:32:44,039
If it's not as wet as in Charlestown,
I could use the change.

329
00:32:44,098 --> 00:32:47,698
Then get the narcotics running,
starting in Tampa.

330
00:32:48,068 --> 00:32:49,801
Frank Ormino runs Tampa.

331
00:32:49,861 --> 00:32:51,861
He's gonna decide
he doesn't need the headache.

332
00:32:52,386 --> 00:32:55,852
When's he gonna decide that?
10 minutes after you get there.

333
00:32:56,036 --> 00:32:59,136
I see, so I gotta make you
and me equal partners?

334
00:32:59,479 --> 00:33:01,813
No! Frank Ormino's an equal partner.

335
00:33:02,210 --> 00:33:06,543
But look what's gonna to happen to him.
I guess I work cheap.

336
00:33:07,683 --> 00:33:09,983
Can you tolerate
an Irishman in your crew?

337
00:33:10,376 --> 00:33:13,142
This is America. I've lived worse.

338
00:33:17,296 --> 00:33:22,329
<i>Ybor City Station Florida</i>

339
00:33:29,797 --> 00:33:32,797
I realized it's not
enough to break the rules.

340
00:33:34,245 --> 00:33:37,578
You have to be strong enough
to make your own.

341
00:34:01,434 --> 00:34:03,434
Joseph!

342
00:34:07,247 --> 00:34:09,480
How ya doin'? You! Look at you!

343
00:34:09,982 --> 00:34:13,349
Hey, sorry about your father.
Yeah, sorry about your brother.

344
00:34:13,705 --> 00:34:15,604
Thank you, thank you

345
00:34:15,605 --> 00:34:18,305
Listen, when Lefty Downer
found me in Montreal...

346
00:34:18,310 --> 00:34:20,492
...told me the Pescatores wanted
me to come work for them...

347
00:34:20,507 --> 00:34:22,807
I thought it was a straight bamboozle.

348
00:34:22,944 --> 00:34:24,344
Then I thought...

349
00:34:24,352 --> 00:34:28,673
...if anyone could charm the devil,
it's my old partner. Look at this!

350
00:34:28,830 --> 00:34:31,796
Holy shit! Would you look at this?

351
00:34:31,980 --> 00:34:34,647
Here, after you.
Get the fuck outta here!

352
00:34:34,686 --> 00:34:37,286
I work for you now, Boss Joe Coughlin.

353
00:34:37,425 --> 00:34:41,492
Reach under the seat
and you'll find a friend.

354
00:34:47,288 --> 00:34:48,488
Welcome to Ybor.

355
00:34:48,741 --> 00:34:49,892
The Harlem of Tampa.

356
00:34:50,511 --> 00:34:54,378
The gods built this place.
What you're smellin' now...

357
00:34:54,415 --> 00:34:56,315
...probably bolos or empanadas.

358
00:34:56,823 --> 00:34:58,790
The rest of Tampa leaves Ybor alone.

359
00:34:59,142 --> 00:35:00,309
As far as they're concerned...

360
00:35:00,374 --> 00:35:02,309
...we're a bunch of dirty
Spics and Whops and...

361
00:35:02,310 --> 00:35:03,909
...we can fuck off and
do what we need to do...

362
00:35:04,109 --> 00:35:05,209
...as long as we leave them alone.

363
00:35:05,293 --> 00:35:06,560
You'd think we could all get along...

364
00:35:06,660 --> 00:35:09,160
...but it don't work out that way.

365
00:35:09,556 --> 00:35:13,023
The Italians and the Cubans
keep to themselves.

366
00:35:13,446 --> 00:35:15,546
But the Cubans, they hate the Spaniards.

367
00:35:15,610 --> 00:35:18,046
And the Spaniards look at all
Cubans like they're uppity Coons...

368
00:35:18,246 --> 00:35:21,225
...who forgot their place since
America freed them in '98.

369
00:35:21,425 --> 00:35:24,788
The Cubans and the Spanish,
they look down on the Puerto Ricans...

370
00:35:24,988 --> 00:35:27,588
...and everyone, I mean everyone,
shits on the Dominicans.

371
00:35:27,825 --> 00:35:30,258
The Italians only respect you
if you came off the boat.

372
00:35:30,458 --> 00:35:31,558
How you doing, Laney?

373
00:35:31,591 --> 00:35:34,324
And the white people think anyone
gives a shit what they think.

374
00:35:35,586 --> 00:35:37,086
You're a fuckin' piece of work.

375
00:35:53,703 --> 00:35:55,203
Port of Tampa!

376
00:36:02,116 --> 00:36:04,183
Who is it? Fireplace..

377
00:36:13,678 --> 00:36:15,078
Thanks, JT. No worries.

378
00:36:16,776 --> 00:36:20,709
There is a whole network of tunnels
like this underneath the city.

379
00:36:22,302 --> 00:36:25,035
Who owns this warehouse?
Frank Ormino did.

380
00:36:25,420 --> 00:36:26,720
What do you mean Ormino did?

381
00:36:27,281 --> 00:36:29,614
Ormino sprung a few leaks the other day.

382
00:36:33,070 --> 00:36:35,037
That was quick. Look at this over here.

383
00:36:35,154 --> 00:36:37,354
The best money can buy.

384
00:36:37,444 --> 00:36:39,977
You gotta keep it at 186 Fahrenheit.

385
00:36:41,236 --> 00:36:43,436
Yeah, these babies never lie.

386
00:36:43,845 --> 00:36:47,111
Try to keep people from dying
when they drink your hootch.

387
00:36:47,143 --> 00:36:48,743
Made a lot of toilet booze in prison,

388
00:36:48,856 --> 00:36:51,189
...looks to me like you're
missing two key ingredients.

389
00:36:51,349 --> 00:36:53,149
Which are? People and glasses.

390
00:36:53,383 --> 00:36:55,716
Yeah, we got a problem. Why?

391
00:36:56,024 --> 00:36:58,224
Our distributor...
he's been comin' up empty.

392
00:36:58,324 --> 00:36:59,824
What is this?

393
00:36:59,869 --> 00:37:02,102
The boats have been sinkin'
What's his name?

394
00:37:02,187 --> 00:37:03,187
Gary L. Smith.

395
00:37:03,804 --> 00:37:05,004
Gary Elsmith.

396
00:37:05,141 --> 00:37:07,541
No, Gary L. Smith

397
00:37:07,801 --> 00:37:09,067
It's a middle initial. I don't know...

398
00:37:09,267 --> 00:37:11,467
...he wants people to use it.
It's a Southern thing.

399
00:37:11,523 --> 00:37:14,856
Not just an asshole thing? Both!

400
00:37:18,024 --> 00:37:19,424
Thank you, Miss Roe.

401
00:37:20,119 --> 00:37:21,786
You must be Maso's new find.

402
00:37:22,592 --> 00:37:23,592
Well, I guess, somethin' like that.

403
00:37:24,683 --> 00:37:26,092
How ya doin'?

404
00:37:28,439 --> 00:37:30,306
So what brings you by?

405
00:37:30,503 --> 00:37:33,536
I've been asked to take over
Frank Ormino's affairs.

406
00:37:33,627 --> 00:37:36,527
Hope that's not permanent! No offense.

407
00:37:36,940 --> 00:37:38,540
None taken. Why is that?

408
00:37:38,610 --> 00:37:41,277
Folks like dealing with who they know...

409
00:37:41,390 --> 00:37:42,957
...and nobody knows you.

410
00:37:43,094 --> 00:37:45,294
I see. Well, what would you suggest?

411
00:37:45,638 --> 00:37:47,438
I have no ambitions for it but...

412
00:37:48,381 --> 00:37:51,781
...to keep continuity...
...instead of doin' it for a term.

413
00:37:52,007 --> 00:37:55,107
Well, we're mostly concerned with
why the last 3 supply runs were hit.

414
00:37:55,216 --> 00:37:58,116
Well, that's the Cubans.
Then let's just go to a new supplier.

415
00:37:58,509 --> 00:38:00,776
It's not that simple. Why not?

416
00:38:02,072 --> 00:38:04,706
Well, because they're all paying
tribute to the Suarez family.

417
00:38:05,771 --> 00:38:07,804
That's the Cubans that are all
down in that club on 7th, right?

418
00:38:07,810 --> 00:38:09,504
We're going to need to
talk to them soon.

419
00:38:12,318 --> 00:38:16,318
I'm afraid you don't understand
how things are done here.

420
00:38:16,390 --> 00:38:20,823
I deal with Mr. Suarez and his sister.

421
00:38:25,410 --> 00:38:29,276
If you want, I'm sure we can arrange
a table by tomorrow night, 9 o'clock.

422
00:38:29,371 --> 00:38:30,571
Great!

423
00:38:30,665 --> 00:38:34,265
Now, Gary L., tell me this.
Do you work directly for Albert White?

424
00:38:34,337 --> 00:38:37,004
Or is there some intermediary
I should know about as well?

425
00:38:37,081 --> 00:38:38,681
What? We marked your bottles.

426
00:38:39,284 --> 00:38:41,784
You what?
If you distilled it, we marked it.

427
00:38:42,279 --> 00:38:45,012
And all these runs that
were supposedly lost at sea...

428
00:38:45,098 --> 00:38:48,112
somehow made their way
into Albert White's speakeasies.

429
00:38:48,910 --> 00:38:50,410
Can you explain that?

430
00:38:50,515 --> 00:38:51,982
No, I don't understand.

431
00:38:52,404 --> 00:38:55,204
Dion drove me by your house
on the way over here.

432
00:38:55,221 --> 00:38:56,288
You got a lovely place.

433
00:38:56,377 --> 00:38:58,488
You're gonna have
to bag up all that shit...

434
00:38:58,508 --> 00:39:00,288
and send it to wherever
it is you're going.

435
00:39:00,300 --> 00:39:03,386
Where am I goin'? Are you fuckin' her?

436
00:39:03,429 --> 00:39:05,929
What? Who? Miss Roe.

437
00:39:06,465 --> 00:39:07,465
What?

438
00:39:07,590 --> 00:39:09,765
He's fuckin' her!
Without question, definitely.

439
00:39:09,775 --> 00:39:12,808
Aw, c'mon! Afternoon taste of Miss Roe?

440
00:39:13,142 --> 00:39:17,309
Sugar in the mornin', sugar in...whatever.
I don't care what, who you fuck...

441
00:39:17,324 --> 00:39:21,291
Here's some tickets.
This is the 11 o'clock Seaboard tonight.

442
00:39:21,427 --> 00:39:25,194
I don't care who you take with you
but you gotta be on that train.

443
00:39:25,894 --> 00:39:29,646
Wait a minute! Wait a minute, gentlemen.
come on, a second here.

444
00:39:29,716 --> 00:39:30,916
Look, if you don't do the whole thing...

445
00:39:31,116 --> 00:39:33,416
I can bounce your head off the
floor like a fuckin' bowling ball...

446
00:39:33,616 --> 00:39:34,716
...but let's just make it easy.

447
00:39:34,731 --> 00:39:37,431
Put yourself on that train, Gary L...

448
00:39:37,594 --> 00:39:40,194
Or we're gonna have to put you under it.

449
00:39:40,359 --> 00:39:42,059
Listen, I think...can we...?

450
00:39:42,378 --> 00:39:46,256
Oh, no...c'mon, fellas...gentlemen...
Let's just sit and visit with each other.

451
00:39:46,736 --> 00:39:47,969
Is this...?

452
00:39:49,661 --> 00:39:51,161
Mr. Cou...

453
00:39:54,135 --> 00:39:57,812
<i>Francis Ormino found shot
Police seek witnesses</i>

454
00:39:58,770 --> 00:40:04,503
When did you mark the bottles?
Frick are you talking about?

455
00:40:04,651 --> 00:40:07,051
You been with me every
second since I been here...

456
00:40:07,251 --> 00:40:08,451
...you see me mark any bottles?

457
00:40:08,476 --> 00:40:10,946
No,
that's how come I know it was bullshit!

458
00:40:58,636 --> 00:41:01,069
Mr. Suarez, nice to see you.

459
00:41:01,745 --> 00:41:04,245
Let me introduce you to Joe Coughlin.

460
00:41:04,302 --> 00:41:05,902
Pleasure to meet you, sir.

461
00:41:07,677 --> 00:41:09,277
Have a drink.

462
00:41:10,088 --> 00:41:11,088
Thank you very much.

463
00:41:12,002 --> 00:41:14,235
I never agreed with the Spanish...

464
00:41:14,236 --> 00:41:16,036
...that the lighter rums were superior.

465
00:41:16,465 --> 00:41:18,965
Of course, we Cubans went along...

466
00:41:19,050 --> 00:41:20,950
because or our obsession that
light is greater in all things.

467
00:41:22,065 --> 00:41:25,298
Dion, Joseph! My sister, Graciela.
Nice to meet you.

468
00:41:25,550 --> 00:41:27,950
We've met.
My mistake. Of course, we've met.

469
00:41:28,219 --> 00:41:29,219
Yes, we have.

470
00:41:30,446 --> 00:41:33,312
How you doin'?
Hi, how are you? Nice to meet you.

471
00:41:34,249 --> 00:41:35,749
God, this rum is incredible!

472
00:41:36,592 --> 00:41:38,592
It would be nice if
we could sell it up North.

473
00:41:38,655 --> 00:41:40,555
When your country
treats you like adults.

474
00:41:40,620 --> 00:41:42,220
Oh, I'd even be out of a job.

475
00:41:43,587 --> 00:41:44,987
Esteban took those.

476
00:41:46,049 --> 00:41:48,582
The working people of Miami. Very good!

477
00:41:48,736 --> 00:41:52,336
It is a hobby. Perhaps I photograph
you someday, Mr. Coughlin?

478
00:41:52,356 --> 00:41:54,756
I don't know about that. The fewer
pictures of me out there, the better.

479
00:41:54,956 --> 00:41:56,356
I'm with the Indians on that one.

480
00:41:59,718 --> 00:42:00,818
Speaking of captured souls...

481
00:42:03,623 --> 00:42:07,523
I am told that Mr Gary L. Smith was
seen boarding a Seaboard Limited.

482
00:42:07,606 --> 00:42:10,806
with his wife in one Pullman
and that puta maestra in the other.

483
00:42:11,167 --> 00:42:12,467
Well, you never know.

484
00:42:12,513 --> 00:42:15,646
Sometimes a change of scenery
can do a man good.

485
00:42:15,731 --> 00:42:18,731
Is that why you're here in Ybor?
A little change of scenery?

486
00:42:18,810 --> 00:42:21,943
I'm here in Ybor to distill and
distribute the demon rum.

487
00:42:22,037 --> 00:42:25,371
A task which is made more difficult
by your erratic import schedules.

488
00:42:25,543 --> 00:42:27,110
We don't control the tides.

489
00:42:27,175 --> 00:42:29,310
The tides would be fine
if we were in Miami.

490
00:42:29,394 --> 00:42:31,594
We know nothing of the boats to Miami.

491
00:42:31,612 --> 00:42:35,112
Senor Famosa assures me
the tides have been calm all summer.

492
00:42:37,446 --> 00:42:39,346
When you say Senor Famosa's name...

493
00:42:39,532 --> 00:42:41,832
...so we worry you may
overtake our supply routes.

494
00:42:42,866 --> 00:42:45,166
No, I use Senor Famosa's name...

495
00:42:45,170 --> 00:42:49,047
...to reassure you that from now on,
you can work directly with me...

496
00:42:49,077 --> 00:42:51,277
...and you can charge me a higher price.

497
00:42:51,471 --> 00:42:52,971
What do we get in return?

498
00:42:53,247 --> 00:42:57,247
You get access to Ormino's cops
and judges, which we now control.

499
00:42:57,288 --> 00:43:00,388
Most of whom wouldn't do business
with you otherwise because you're Cuban.

500
00:43:00,589 --> 00:43:02,489
And you would want
exclusive access to our molasses?

501
00:43:02,696 --> 00:43:05,196
Nope. You just can't sell
to the White operation.

502
00:43:05,333 --> 00:43:07,300
Albert White is a paying customer.

503
00:43:07,752 --> 00:43:10,252
We've never had a problem with him.

504
00:43:10,339 --> 00:43:11,339
I know Albert White.

505
00:43:11,719 --> 00:43:15,219
I thought you might like to deal with
someone who treated you like a human being.

506
00:43:15,762 --> 00:43:17,995
It is possible this
will bring bloodshed.

507
00:43:18,095 --> 00:43:20,695
This will definitely bring bloodshed.

508
00:43:23,167 --> 00:43:25,767
These are very favorable terms.

509
00:43:29,276 --> 00:43:31,676
Albert White is what we get.

510
00:43:34,261 --> 00:43:36,228
The local sheriff wanted to see us.

511
00:43:36,285 --> 00:43:37,985
Apparently it was a custom down there...

512
00:43:38,185 --> 00:43:39,985
...to talk about how
you were going to break the law...

513
00:43:39,990 --> 00:43:41,450
...before you did it.

514
00:43:41,504 --> 00:43:45,304
What kind of guy is the Chief?
Well, he's a cop, so he's an asshole.

515
00:43:45,349 --> 00:43:47,649
Beyond that, he's ok.

516
00:43:52,970 --> 00:43:55,203
What are you doing?
Don't fuck with the guy's stuff!

517
00:43:55,404 --> 00:43:59,304
The Sheriff's gonna come in and find some
dago goin' through his fuckin' papers.

518
00:44:03,431 --> 00:44:05,131
Hey, this is Vegas right here.

519
00:44:11,182 --> 00:44:12,782
Please, sit down.

520
00:44:20,604 --> 00:44:22,704
I won't insult you by...

521
00:44:23,551 --> 00:44:26,251
...asking the nature of your business...

522
00:44:27,124 --> 00:44:29,924
...so you won't have
to insult me by lying.

523
00:44:31,569 --> 00:44:33,047
Is that fair?

524
00:44:34,237 --> 00:44:35,739
Sounds fair to me.

525
00:44:36,031 --> 00:44:39,288
Is it true you're a
police captain's son?

526
00:44:39,372 --> 00:44:40,846
Yes, sir!

527
00:44:40,953 --> 00:44:43,570
You serve overseas? France.

528
00:44:44,959 --> 00:44:46,778
Tell it to the Marines.

529
00:44:46,813 --> 00:44:50,011
Yes, sir. They told it to us.

530
00:44:50,096 --> 00:44:53,167
I was a soldier and then a US Marshall.

531
00:44:54,225 --> 00:44:56,692
I killed 7 men in my lifetime.

532
00:44:56,898 --> 00:45:01,288
Truth be told,
their faces haunt me most nights.

533
00:45:08,662 --> 00:45:11,877
You keep your business
north of Second...

534
00:45:11,912 --> 00:45:16,058
...south of 27th and east of Nebraska.

535
00:45:17,506 --> 00:45:20,872
You and I will have little
in the way of discord.

536
00:45:20,907 --> 00:45:22,140
Sounds good.

537
00:45:22,683 --> 00:45:25,192
I know we live in a fallen world...

538
00:45:26,148 --> 00:45:29,541
...but just because I breathe corrupt air...

539
00:45:29,861 --> 00:45:32,811
...rub elbows with corrupt men...

540
00:45:34,159 --> 00:45:38,807
Never make the mistake of
thinking that I am corruptible.

541
00:45:40,247 --> 00:45:42,188
I won't make that mistake.

542
00:45:45,255 --> 00:45:48,642
Oh, I'm sorry. Thought you were alone.

543
00:45:48,720 --> 00:45:51,958
That's alright, Loretta.
These gentlemen were just leaving.

544
00:45:51,993 --> 00:45:53,790
Honey, your manners.

545
00:45:54,351 --> 00:45:55,939
Oh, yes, Father.

546
00:45:57,985 --> 00:46:00,041
Miss Loretta Figgis.

547
00:46:00,237 --> 00:46:02,409
Pleased to meet you, Miss.
I'm Joe Coughlin.

548
00:46:02,444 --> 00:46:07,630
Dion Bartolo. Loretta is taking
the train on a long journey today.

549
00:46:07,871 --> 00:46:09,364
It's goin' around.

550
00:46:09,581 --> 00:46:12,128
Is that right?

551
00:46:12,163 --> 00:46:14,465
She gonna be a star in Hollywood.

552
00:46:14,549 --> 00:46:17,136
It's only a screen test, Daddy.
No.

553
00:46:17,220 --> 00:46:21,524
A screen agent came here
and picked out a few girls.

554
00:46:22,477 --> 00:46:25,035
My brother's out there.
Your brother's in Hollywood?

555
00:46:25,189 --> 00:46:27,291
He's a stuntman, I'm told.

556
00:46:27,326 --> 00:46:28,941
Fallin' off horses.

557
00:46:29,655 --> 00:46:32,783
Pleased to meet you, Miss. Chief.

558
00:46:33,577 --> 00:46:34,910
Gentlemen.

559
00:46:36,329 --> 00:46:38,251
You sure you don't want a banana?
No, it's alright.

560
00:46:38,331 --> 00:46:42,339
You can't get fruit like this in Boston.
I know, it looks good.

561
00:46:43,465 --> 00:46:45,003
Watch!
There she is.

562
00:46:45,038 --> 00:46:47,643
Just watch this! Yeah?

563
00:46:49,391 --> 00:46:53,730
Hello! Good afternoon! How are you?

564
00:46:53,765 --> 00:46:56,367
I'm well. How are you?
Excellent!

565
00:46:56,902 --> 00:47:00,909
You and your brother
come to any decision on...

566
00:47:02,579 --> 00:47:05,528
Not yet. We're still considering,
Mr. Coughlin. Okay.

567
00:47:06,040 --> 00:47:09,031
Yes, it would be quite an upheaval for us.

568
00:47:09,066 --> 00:47:12,533
I understand. Of course.
We don't make changes easily.

569
00:47:12,840 --> 00:47:15,539
Well, there's all kind of change.

570
00:47:15,574 --> 00:47:20,269
Where I was recently staying,
we used to play chess a lot...

571
00:47:20,304 --> 00:47:24,252
...this is the kind of change where you
get your pawn to the end of the board...

572
00:47:24,352 --> 00:47:27,920
...and it changes into a queen.
There's not a lot to think about here.

573
00:47:28,070 --> 00:47:30,944
Yes. I do play chess.
You do?

574
00:47:30,979 --> 00:47:33,017
My father taught me.

575
00:47:33,162 --> 00:47:34,756
What you might do well
to remember is that...

576
00:47:34,856 --> 00:47:37,256
...the pawn and the king
end up in the same box...

577
00:47:37,260 --> 00:47:38,932
...at the end of the game.

578
00:47:39,420 --> 00:47:42,796
Man! It's not about the end.

579
00:47:43,009 --> 00:47:45,517
It's about when you're playin' the game.

580
00:47:45,552 --> 00:47:48,392
You hang me upside down
and light me on fire at the end.

581
00:47:48,476 --> 00:47:50,310
I want to win while I'm playin'.

582
00:47:54,694 --> 00:47:57,418
I have feeling you win
most of the games you play.

583
00:47:57,820 --> 00:48:00,166
Not yet...but I plan on it.

584
00:48:01,580 --> 00:48:02,742
Why don't you join me?

585
00:49:11,010 --> 00:49:14,300
You know, some people say
that liquor is only a side business.

586
00:49:14,808 --> 00:49:16,112
Is that so?

587
00:49:16,147 --> 00:49:20,773
In fact, I heard rumors you
give most of your money away.

588
00:49:20,857 --> 00:49:22,852
A lot of it in Cuba.

589
00:49:23,946 --> 00:49:25,506
Anything that's foolish?

590
00:49:25,823 --> 00:49:29,087
Not foolish,
Just not my cause, that's all.

591
00:49:29,745 --> 00:49:31,332
What is your cause?

592
00:49:31,665 --> 00:49:33,705
Distribution of Demon Rum.

593
00:49:35,170 --> 00:49:37,730
And no man should rule
another man's life.

594
00:49:40,429 --> 00:49:43,332
If you corner the rum market,
you will be a king.

595
00:49:44,766 --> 00:49:46,602
I'll still have to deal
with Albert White.

596
00:49:46,686 --> 00:49:49,443
But how will you hold the
power, once you have it?

597
00:49:49,527 --> 00:49:51,925
Why, you don't think I'm strong enough?

598
00:49:52,361 --> 00:49:54,807
I don't know if you're cruel enough.

599
00:49:56,323 --> 00:50:00,463
And if you are, that would be very sad.

600
00:50:01,123 --> 00:50:03,183
Powerful men don't have to be cruel.

601
00:50:03,964 --> 00:50:05,610
But they usually are.

602
00:50:07,383 --> 00:50:10,803
Tell me something, do you think there
is such a thing as an noble man?

603
00:50:10,888 --> 00:50:15,039
I have nothing against noble men.
They just rarely live past 40.

604
00:50:17,146 --> 00:50:19,109
My father died for Cuba.

605
00:50:19,986 --> 00:50:22,020
My mother died of a broken heart.

606
00:50:23,655 --> 00:50:25,449
He would often tell us,
Esteban and I...

607
00:50:25,533 --> 00:50:29,747
"You can not truly live unless there
is something for which you would die."

608
00:50:31,250 --> 00:50:32,979
Sounds like a good man.

609
00:50:34,591 --> 00:50:35,965
He was.

610
00:51:32,129 --> 00:51:34,993
We will never be lovers.
No?

611
00:51:37,554 --> 00:51:39,183
Why's that?

612
00:51:41,936 --> 00:51:43,561
We will not be lovers.

613
00:52:49,533 --> 00:52:52,545
<i>We cornered the rum market
and lived like kings</i>

614
00:52:55,126 --> 00:52:56,419
Fast. Come on. Hurry up.

615
00:52:59,508 --> 00:53:02,365
<i>Banks collapsed. Jobs dried up.</i>

616
00:53:02,565 --> 00:53:07,465
<i>But vice, it seemed,
was Depression-proof</i>

617
00:53:08,392 --> 00:53:09,479
Okay. Let's go.

618
00:53:14,153 --> 00:53:18,358
<i>The Suarez-Coughlin partnership
created a rare stability.</i>

619
00:53:36,809 --> 00:53:40,603
<i>We paid off Albert's guys in Central
Florida to put down their guns.</i>

620
00:53:42,650 --> 00:53:46,275
<i>So when Albert wanted to hit us
he had to use his Miami crews.</i>

621
00:53:50,846 --> 00:53:53,456
<i>When they showed up,
we bushwhacked them.</i>

622
00:54:12,862 --> 00:54:15,408
<i>Albert was living on the run in Miami...</i>

623
00:54:15,488 --> 00:54:19,413
<i>and there wasn't a speak in Central
or North Florida we didn't sell to.</i>

624
00:54:52,752 --> 00:54:55,602
Send them in there,
put this shit out. Alright.

625
00:54:59,067 --> 00:55:00,116
Get on the floor!

626
00:55:00,151 --> 00:55:01,477
Get down! Now!

627
00:55:01,567 --> 00:55:03,767
Get on the floor!
Get down!

628
00:55:04,267 --> 00:55:05,967
Get down! Get Down!

629
00:55:09,375 --> 00:55:13,673
This is what happens when
Catholics try to sell liquor down here.

630
00:55:13,757 --> 00:55:16,468
The guy's name is R.D. Pruitt.

631
00:55:16,503 --> 00:55:18,867
Well, we better go find him.

632
00:55:18,973 --> 00:55:20,940
He is in the Clan.
So what?

633
00:55:20,975 --> 00:55:24,499
So are 5 million other guys in this country.
The clan has a lot of fuckin' juice.

634
00:55:24,534 --> 00:55:26,571
They're inbreds with
4th grade educations.

635
00:55:26,606 --> 00:55:28,261
Oh. They're gonna love you.

636
00:55:28,296 --> 00:55:31,390
A Catholic who works with coloreds
and lives with the Cubans.

637
00:55:31,951 --> 00:55:34,304
The bigger problem is
R.D.'s brother-in-law.

638
00:55:34,339 --> 00:55:36,746
Who'ss he?
Chief Figgis.

639
00:55:53,000 --> 00:55:54,595
Joe Coughlin.

640
00:55:55,582 --> 00:55:57,709
I don't shake hands with Papists.

641
00:55:58,168 --> 00:55:59,806
No offense.

642
00:55:59,841 --> 00:56:01,223
None taken.

643
00:56:01,255 --> 00:56:04,536
It help if I tell you I haven't
been to church in half of my life?

644
00:56:07,135 --> 00:56:08,895
Alright, now.

645
00:56:09,261 --> 00:56:11,044
R.D.

646
00:56:11,431 --> 00:56:14,396
Word is your causin'
trouble down in Ybor.

647
00:56:15,518 --> 00:56:16,998
How's that?

648
00:56:18,352 --> 00:56:21,766
Well, we hear you're stickin' up places.

649
00:56:22,856 --> 00:56:25,292
I don't know a damn thing about that.

650
00:56:27,524 --> 00:56:29,607
I'm just playing with you.

651
00:56:30,526 --> 00:56:31,987
You all know that.

652
00:56:34,157 --> 00:56:35,322
R.D.

653
00:56:36,407 --> 00:56:39,756
This is a businessman
who's come here to business...

654
00:56:39,791 --> 00:56:42,493
...and I suggest that
you do it with him.

655
00:56:43,164 --> 00:56:46,717
This man is a bootlegger...

656
00:56:46,752 --> 00:56:49,247
...and a fornicator with niggers.

657
00:56:50,502 --> 00:56:54,903
He needs to be tarred and feathered,
not done business with.

658
00:56:59,425 --> 00:57:02,867
I'm just playin'!
You can take a joke, right?

659
00:57:03,005 --> 00:57:04,529
Sure, I can take a joke.

660
00:57:04,564 --> 00:57:06,693
Not if you become one, right?

661
00:57:11,018 --> 00:57:13,326
So you like the Parisian, right?

662
00:57:13,520 --> 00:57:15,095
And if I did?

663
00:57:15,130 --> 00:57:17,484
I might be able to cut you in
on 10% of the house take.

664
00:57:17,564 --> 00:57:19,585
You'd do that?
I would.

665
00:57:20,996 --> 00:57:25,347
Well, I ought to be worth more than 10%.

666
00:57:25,382 --> 00:57:26,572
What were you thinking?

667
00:57:26,607 --> 00:57:29,646
I was thinking 60.
60 percent?

668
00:57:29,681 --> 00:57:31,395
The biggest club in town?

669
00:57:32,075 --> 00:57:34,798
That's right.
For what exactly?

670
00:57:35,162 --> 00:57:37,886
My friends might look
on you more kindly.

671
00:57:37,921 --> 00:57:40,377
What friends?
50%.

672
00:57:40,412 --> 00:57:43,251
Son, I ain't giving you 60%.
I ain't your son.

673
00:57:44,005 --> 00:57:45,869
Ain't nobody's son.

674
00:57:45,904 --> 00:57:48,341
Save you father some embarrassment.

675
00:57:48,376 --> 00:57:50,275
What's that?
15%.

676
00:57:51,467 --> 00:57:54,765
I will beat you to death.
Excuse me?

677
00:57:55,993 --> 00:57:57,193
You know...

678
00:57:59,097 --> 00:58:01,608
...that does sound like
a fair arrangment.

679
00:58:01,643 --> 00:58:03,906
You go to 20?
I think 15's pretty good...

680
00:58:03,941 --> 00:58:06,681
...for a job you won't
have to show up to work for.

681
00:58:09,090 --> 00:58:12,446
Well, it's a fair deal...

682
00:58:12,481 --> 00:58:14,366
...and I'm pleased to agree to it.

683
00:58:16,323 --> 00:58:19,192
How to I pick up my cut?
Come by the Parisian...

684
00:58:19,227 --> 00:58:21,682
...second Tuesday, every month. 7 o'clock.

685
00:58:21,783 --> 00:58:23,665
Pleasure, Mr. Coughlin.

686
00:58:24,232 --> 00:58:25,722
Irv.

687
00:58:32,752 --> 00:58:34,505
Sounds like we have a deal.

688
00:58:37,588 --> 00:58:39,700
The boy's as dumb as a grape.

689
00:58:43,625 --> 00:58:45,467
I don't understand what Maso wants.

690
00:58:45,502 --> 00:58:49,354
Arrests are down 70%,
revenues up 300%.

691
00:58:49,389 --> 00:58:52,828
I don't like it...some kid sent
down here like we need supervision.

692
00:58:52,863 --> 00:58:54,626
No, no. We don't need supervision.

693
00:58:54,661 --> 00:58:57,809
Digger want to look at the
Casino option, check progress...

694
00:58:57,844 --> 00:58:59,362
...that's all. He's gonna
report back to the old man.

695
00:58:59,397 --> 00:59:01,149
Hey, Joe, don't make a big thing of it.

696
00:59:01,184 --> 00:59:04,689
Maso still gonna listen to what his son
tells him about startin' a new casino.

697
00:59:04,724 --> 00:59:06,009
Don't worry about it.

698
00:59:06,536 --> 00:59:09,000
How'd he get the name Digger?
Because he's a fuckin' dummy.

699
00:59:09,035 --> 00:59:11,942
All they let him do is dig ditches
for the bodies they bump off.

700
00:59:12,075 --> 00:59:13,724
No shit! Yeah!

701
00:59:16,743 --> 00:59:18,349
That's great.

702
00:59:18,384 --> 00:59:23,166
<i>I had come up with a plan to invest in a
casino with stakeholders in Sarasota...</i>

703
00:59:23,201 --> 00:59:25,435
<i>...at the new Ritz development site.</i>

704
00:59:26,126 --> 00:59:27,951
Ritz Hotel and Casino.

705
00:59:27,986 --> 00:59:30,422
Top shelf.
Right to the casino.

706
00:59:30,457 --> 00:59:32,398
Absolute top level resort.

707
00:59:32,433 --> 00:59:36,390
Sure to be a good experience
whether you gamble or not.

708
00:59:40,638 --> 00:59:44,531
<i>For such a violent business it was
populated with surprising number of guys...</i>

709
00:59:44,631 --> 00:59:46,614
<i>...who were just puttin'
food on the table.</i>

710
00:59:47,183 --> 00:59:49,326
<i>Digger wasn't one of those guys.</i>

711
00:59:52,479 --> 00:59:54,052
So this is it.

712
00:59:54,065 --> 00:59:56,509
Volstead Act won't last forever, right?

713
00:59:56,544 --> 00:59:58,416
What we gonna do when Prohibition ends?

714
00:59:58,568 --> 00:59:59,777
Gambling.

715
00:59:59,861 --> 01:00:02,820
We use the connections we put
together to get it legalized...

716
01:00:02,855 --> 01:00:04,944
...and we're the only ones
in place to run it.

717
01:00:04,979 --> 01:00:06,435
And this is it?

718
01:00:06,470 --> 01:00:08,269
Will be. Ritz Longboat Key.

719
01:00:08,304 --> 01:00:10,503
I sat down with the
owners of Sarasota last week.

720
01:00:10,703 --> 01:00:13,231
Why'd they let us in?
Because the can't get gambling legal...

721
01:00:13,331 --> 01:00:14,749
...and they can't run a casino.

722
01:00:14,784 --> 01:00:17,712
The own the property, we run the casino.
We chop the profits 50/50.

723
01:00:17,747 --> 01:00:19,328
Wait a minute.

724
01:00:19,629 --> 01:00:22,550
Do we have a magic
stick for changin' laws?

725
01:00:22,585 --> 01:00:24,542
I heard you got bingo legal.

726
01:00:24,881 --> 01:00:27,930
It's a step. It's like a prerequisite,
you gotta do one thing and then...

727
01:00:27,965 --> 01:00:29,604
Yeah, I know...a prerequisite.

